explanation:
To determine whether any executed operation in OS_MutSemGive is dead code we must know the semantics and side-effects of every call, macro, type and assignment in the function:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Controls whether the function body executes (return value determines the if); may have side effects (token output and possible transactions) so its behavior is essential to know whether inner operations are removable.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro used to obtain the mutex pointer; macros can encapsulate side effects or extra operations, so its expansion is needed to judge removability of the lookup.
- OS_mutex_table: The global table accessed by the macro — needed to see whether indexing/reads have side effects or rely on other state (and whether removing the access changes program behaviour).
- OS_mutex_internal_record_t: Definition of the mutex record (in particular the last_owner field) to know whether writing to last_owner is meaningful (volatile, aliasing, packed bitfield, etc.) or can be removed without effect.
- OS_TaskGetId: Called to obtain self_task; must know whether it has observable side effects (e.g., changes state, depends on timing) or is a pure accessor — affects whether the call is dead.
- OS_ObjectIdEqual: The comparison used only for the debug warning; need to know if it has side effects (unlikely) and thus whether the conditional and debug call can be removed.
- OS_MutSemGive_Impl: Performs the actual give operation; crucial to know its semantics and side effects — removing the outer code but leaving/omitting this call would definitely change behaviour if it does real work.
- OS_DEBUG: Logging macro/function used inside the conditional; many projects define debug macros as no-ops in production — need its definition to decide if the logging call constitutes dead code.
- OS_ObjectIdToInteger: Conversion used only for logging arguments; if conversion has no side effects then the logging call (and conversions) may be removable — must confirm purity.
- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED: Constant assigned to mutex->last_owner; required to know what effect the assignment has and whether it is meaningful to other code.
- OS_SUCCESS: Return-code constant used for the conditional; needed to interpret the precondition for the inner operations.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE: Argument passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; included because it may alter OS_ObjectIdGetById behavior and thereby affect reachability of the body.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: Same reason as OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE — affects OS_ObjectIdGetById semantics and whether the body is executed.
- OS_object_token_t: Type of token used/returned by OS_ObjectIdGetById and passed to Impl; needed to know whether copying/passing has side effects.
- osal_id_t: Type of sem_id and self_task; needed to understand assignment/printing/compare semantics and whether conversions have side effects.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Common helper used by table-access macros/implementations (present in call graph); its behavior may be involved in OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET or OS_MutSemGive_Impl and could introduce side effects relevant to dead-code analysis.

Collectively these symbols let the analyzer determine which operations are purely observational (e.g., logging, pure conversions), which have real state effects (e.g., OS_MutSemGive_Impl, writes to last_owner), and which calls/macros might hide additional side effects — all required to judge whether removing any executed operation would change program behaviour (the MISRA dead-code criterion).
